dismissalText.commentary: Sikandar Raza b Murtagh 50 (56b 4x4 1x6 61m) SR: 89.28

dismissalComment.html: oh dear, this is a horrid shot. Raza skipped down the track to a length delivery and then aimed a wild slog across the line at it. He was nowhere near it, and his head was high as he swung right over the ball, which clattered into the stumps directly.

headshotImage.caption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: canny bowling! Murtagh has done really well to set this dismissal up. The previous two deliveries came in off the seam, but this one just held its line outside off. Chamu pressed forward at it, but played the wrong line expecting seam movement. A feathered edge goes through to O'Brien, and Ireland celebrate.

now what's happened here? Chigumbura jumped down the track and slammed a drive in the air towards Balbirnie at long off. The fielder ran around, caught it just before the ropes, and then managed to maintain his balance and not fall over them. But he was so close to the boundary marker that it's touch and go, and Chigumbura waits at the wicket to receive confirmation that he''s out. There's no television replay, but the Umpires are happy with what they saw, and the fielder's word, and give him out. Shades of that catch by Mooney at the World Cup, though in far less heated circumstances ...

dismissalText.commentary: Tinotenda Mutombodzi run out (Dockrell) 3 (4b 0x4 0x6 12m) SR: 75

dismissalComment.html: run out! This is fantastically sharp work from Dockrell. Jongwe flicked to leg, but the ball didn't get far and Dockrell himself sprinted across at it. Mutombodzi, at the non-striker's end, wanted a single and rushed out, but Jongwe sent him back. Rightly so, as he'd never have made it. Dockrell was across in a flash and shattered the stumps with a bullet throw.

dismissalText.commentary: Luke Jongwe run out (Dockrell/†NJ O'Brien) 8 (5b 1x4 0x6 10m) SR: 160

dismissalComment.html: another run out! Masakadza turned the ball to leg, and called for a run that was never there. Again it was Dockrell's fielding that sealed the dismissal - he sprinted around to midwicket and aimed a perfect throw to Niall O'Brien, who whipped the bails off with the batsman well short.

headshotImage.longCaption: Luke Jongwe, player page headshot cutout 2022

dismissalText.commentary: Paul Stirling c †Mutumbami b Jongwe 50 (92b 4x4 0x6 130m) SR: 54.34

dismissalComment.html: Mutumbami's caught this one! This may have been an even more difficult chance as well. Jongwe hurled down a short ball which may have caught the batsman by surprise. He was late on the pull, and the ball ballooned in the air towards a third or fourth slip position. Mutumbami sprinted to his right, then dived just in time to get a hand underneath the ball. Great effort, and Zimbabwe have removed the in-batsman!

dismissalText.commentary: Andy Balbirnie run out (Sikandar Raza) 24 (43b 2x4 0x6 41m) SR: 55.81

dismissalComment.html: there's no stopping Raza in the field! Balbirnie turned the ball into the leg side, and hit it rather well, but Raza put in a dive from his position at midwicket to cut it off. The batsmen had called for the run, and as Raza stood up he was side on from the wicket, with one stump to aim it. His throw was arrowed directly onto that stump to catch the batsman short, and he breaks the partnership two short of fifty.

image.caption: Tinotenda Mutombodzi at the Under-19 World Cup
image.longCaption: Tinotenda Mutombodzi at the Under-19 World Cup, January 2010

dismissalComment.html: a wicket for the part-timer! Niall O'Brien charged down the track, and with mid-off up he was aiming to go over the off side field. But he couldn't get the required height on the shot, nor the timing, and Chamu Chibhabha moved quickly to his right from cover to hold a catch at waist height.

great catch! This is smart fielding from Nyumbu. Wilson telegraphed his intention to sweep, and Nyumbu immediately started to move from slip towards the leg side as the ball was bowled. The ball took the top edge, going over Mutumbami, but Nyumbu found himself in exactly the right position to pluck an unlikely catch out of the air above his head. He looks as surprised as anyone!

headshotImage.caption: Wellington Masakadza player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Wellington Masakadza player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: caught in the deep! There's only one man out on the leg side, and Joyce has picked him out with a slog sweep. His connection was good, but not nearly good enough, and Chari caught it about three metres inside the boundary. It's a short boundary too, as they're playing on the pitch on the far Western side of the square

caught by Waller in the deep! O'Brien backed himself to beat the fielder with a slog sweep, and he struck the ball really well - but he got rather too far underneath the ball, and achieved more height than distance. Waller set himself under the catch, and waited ... and waited ... and held on! Advantage Zimbabwe now?

dismissalText.commentary: William Porterfield c Sikandar Raza b Muzarabani 20 (20b 3x4 0x6 26m) SR: 100

dismissalComment.html: that's a stunning effort! Porterfield flung himself into a full-blooded drive to a half volley, but he smeared the ball in the air towards extra cover. Raza was in the position, but he had to leap up very high and time his jump just right too. He holds a stinging chance above his head, in mid-air, and Zimbabwe converge on the bowler

dismissalText.commentary: George Dockrell c Nyumbu b Muzarabani 13 (18b 2x4 0x6 36m) SR: 72.22

dismissalComment.html: caught in the gully! Muzarabani charged in and dug the ball in outside off. He got it to leap up at the batsman, and Dockrell tried to ride the bounce, but couldn't. Nyumbu, who'd moved from slip to gully, tumbled forward to hold on to the catch, and Zimbabwe are buzzing now.

headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentTextItems.html: edged! It beats the keeper, it beats a diving short third man, and that's the game!

commentPostTextItems.html: 5.10pm Another cracking finish to a match that ended up much closer than one might have expected after Zimbabwe struggled to 187 all out. Ireland seem to be cruising in the early stages of their chase, but Zimbabwe kept on chipping away and kept the pressure on with some electric fielding once they got the opening. Ireland crept closer and closer, and it was eventually up to their tail to secure a consolatory win. Importantly, this was another good, hard game of cricket between these two teams, who've never produced a boring day out. Why don't they play each other more often? Why aren't Zimbabwe playing a Test match at Stormont next summer?

Thanks for tuning in to another engaging day of cricket between Zimbabwe and Ireland. Your commentator today has been none other than Liam Brickhill, live from Harare Sports Club. I do hope you've enjoyed my coverage, and see you again next time. Until then, goodbye!
Vidy: "It would have been a great week for Ireland if they had won the series as their Rugby team beat France to moved to QF in Rugby WC AND their soccer team beat current champion Germany."

commentTextItems.html: Ireland are on the brink now, Murtagh finding the gap between midwicket and mid-on with a firm clip to get three more.

commentPostTextItems.html: Mark: "Now you know why Middlesex fans call Tim Murtagh "The Lambeth Lara". He used to be almost a geuine allrounder in his younger days."

commentTextItems.html: a huge heave, and he's missed it completely! No need for that shot. Murtagh just slogged across the line at a full one.
fuller and straighter from the bowler, and Murtagh steps forward to drive to mid off.

commentPreTextItems.html: Chigumbura is cycling through his bowlers, and now he brings Muzarabani back on from the Golf Course end. No slip in place.

commentTextItems.html: crunched to the cover boundary! Murtagh is taking his side home here. The ball was wide of off, so the shot was on, but he had to beat a packed inner ring.
pitching on middle, spinning towards off, and the batsman leans forward to defend it back down the track.

headshotImage.caption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Luke Jongwe, player page headshot cutout 2022
headshotImage.longCaption: Luke Jongwe, player page headshot cutout 2022

commentTextItems.html: edged, but it's quite far to Raza's left at slip and he can't reach it.
swept to fine leg! Raza is after it from slip, and hauls it back in.

commentPreTextItems.html: Nyumbu also doesn't have any protection on the cover boundary, so he's being asked to do a difficult job here.

commentTextItems.html: defended back down the track, the ball bang on target.
too straight again from Nyumbu, and he's flicked to midwicket.
almost chipped back to the bowler! Murtagh wanted to drive down the ground, and almost popped it straight back to the bowler.
and Jongwe ends with a sharp bouncer to have the batsman ducking for cover. Good, aggressive delivery, and importantly it's on target.

headshotImage.caption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Luke Jongwe, player page headshot cutout 2022
headshotImage.longCaption: Luke Jongwe, player page headshot cutout 2022

commentTextItems.html: that's a great shot for a no. 10! Zimbabwe have a packed off-side field, with only three men on the leg side, and Murtagh whipped the ball through midwicket in fine fashion. It didn't have the legs to reach the boundary, but they don't need it to.
full and on the legs again, and McBrine works him through midwicket for one.

commentPostTextItems.html: Ireland can do this in singles, no need for any big shots.

commentTextItems.html: a huge lbw appeal! He was certainly struck in front, and height wasn't an issue, but it looked to have pitched well outside leg.
a much straighter line, and McBrine taps it back to the bowler.

commentPreTextItems.html: And now Luke Jongwe is brought on from the Golf Course End. He's had some good spells for Zimbabwe at the death this season, and his captain will probably be asking for yorkers from him.

commentTextItems.html: not quite the yorker, and in fact it's more of a wide half volley. Fortunately for Zimbabwe, he cracks it straight to Waller at point. There's no one on the cover boundary.
clubbed out into the leg side again, but along the ground this time, and they're back for the second.

commentPostTextItems.html: srini: "All Irish batsmen seem to possess a decent batting average. Game on!"

headshotImage.caption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Tim Murtagh player page headshot cutout, 2021

commentTextItems.html: he's found the boundary! With mid on up, Murtagh swung powerfully across the line and over the fielder's head.

commentPreTextItems.html: Zimbabwe had a 7-3 field there, so Nyumbu was definitely bowling too straight. But now they're bringing Waller around to plug the gap at midwicket.

commentTextItems.html: Waller is immediately into action, stopping a flick to leg.

Shades of that catch by Mooney at the World Cup, though in far less heated circumstances ...

dismissalComment.html: canny bowling! Murtagh has done really well to set this dismissal up. The previous two deliveries came in off the seam, but this one just held its line outside off. Chamu pressed forward at it, but played the wrong line expecting seam movement. A feathered edge goes through to O'Brien, and Ireland celebrate.

dismissalText.commentary: Tinotenda Mutombodzi run out (Dockrell) 3 (4b 0x4 0x6 12m) SR: 75

dismissalComment.html: run out! This is fantastically sharp work from Dockrell. Jongwe flicked to leg, but the ball didn't get far and Dockrell himself sprinted across at it. Mutombodzi, at the non-striker's end, wanted a single and rushed out, but Jongwe sent him back. Rightly so, as he'd never have made it. Dockrell was across in a flash and shattered the stumps with a bullet throw.

dismissalText.commentary: Luke Jongwe run out (Dockrell/†NJ O'Brien) 8 (5b 1x4 0x6 10m) SR: 160

dismissalComment.html: another run out! Masakadza turned the ball to leg, and called for a run that was never there. Again it was Dockrell's fielding that sealed the dismissal - he sprinted around to midwicket and aimed a perfect throw to Niall O'Brien, who whipped the bails off with the batsman well short.

dismissalComment.html: there goes another one! Wellington was trying to clear the infield, who had been brought in as Ireland attacked the tail. He got a full ball on off stump, but sliced right underneath it and Kevin O'Brien settled easily under the chance at mid-off.

dismissalText.commentary: Taurai Muzarabani lbw b KJ O'Brien 3 (13b 0x4 0x6 16m) SR: 23.07

dismissalComment.html: got him! O'Brien ends the innings by pinging Muzarabani's pads with a full, straight delivery.

dismissalText.commentary: William Porterfield c Sikandar Raza b Muzarabani 20 (20b 3x4 0x6 26m) SR: 100

dismissalComment.html: that's a stunning effort! Porterfield flung himself into a full-blooded drive to a half volley, but he smeared the ball in the air towards extra cover. Raza was in the position, but he had to leap up very high and time his jump just right too. He holds a stinging chance above his head, in mid-air, and Zimbabwe converge on the bowler

headshotImage.caption: Luke Jongwe, player page headshot cutout 2022
headshotImage.longCaption: Luke Jongwe, player page headshot cutout 2022

dismissalText.commentary: Paul Stirling c †Mutumbami b Jongwe 50 (92b 4x4 0x6 130m) SR: 54.34

dismissalComment.html: Mutumbami's caught this one! This may have been an even more difficult chance as well. Jongwe hurled down a short ball which may have caught the batsman by surprise. He was late on the pull, and the ball ballooned in the air towards a third or fourth slip position. Mutumbami sprinted to his right, then dived just in time to get a hand underneath the ball. Great effort, and Zimbabwe have removed the in-batsman!

headshotImage.caption: Wellington Masakadza player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Wellington Masakadza player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Brian Chari player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Brian Chari player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Ed Joyce c Chari b Masakadza 7 (24b 1x4 0x6 24m) SR: 29.16

dismissalComment.html: caught in the deep! There's only one man out on the leg side, and Joyce has picked him out with a slog sweep. His connection was good, but not nearly good enough, and Chari caught it about three metres inside the boundary. It's a short boundary too, as they're playing on the pitch on the far Western side of the square

dismissalText.commentary: Andy Balbirnie run out (Sikandar Raza) 24 (43b 2x4 0x6 41m) SR: 55.81

dismissalComment.html: there's no stopping Raza in the field! Balbirnie turned the ball into the leg side, and hit it rather well, but Raza put in a dive from his position at midwicket to cut it off. The batsmen had called for the run, and as Raza stood up he was side on from the wicket, with one stump to aim it. His throw was arrowed directly onto that stump to catch the batsman short, and he breaks the partnership two short of fifty.

image.caption: Tinotenda Mutombodzi at the Under-19 World Cup
image.longCaption: Tinotenda Mutombodzi at the Under-19 World Cup, January 2010

dismissalText.commentary: Niall O'Brien c Chibhabha b Mutombodzi 1 (8b 0x4 0x6 14m) SR: 12.5

dismissalComment.html: a wicket for the part-timer! Niall O'Brien charged down the track, and with mid-off up he was aiming to go over the off side field. But he couldn't get the required height on the shot, nor the timing, and Chamu Chibhabha moved quickly to his right from cover to hold a catch at waist height.

image.caption: Tinotenda Mutombodzi at the Under-19 World Cup
image.longCaption: Tinotenda Mutombodzi at the Under-19 World Cup, January 2010

dismissalText.commentary: Gary Wilson c Nyumbu b Mutombodzi 19 (28b 3x4 0x6 47m) SR: 67.85

dismissalComment.html: great catch! This is smart fielding from Nyumbu. Wilson telegraphed his intention to sweep, and Nyumbu immediately started to move from slip towards the leg side as the ball was bowled. The ball took the top edge, going over Mutumbami, but Nyumbu found himself in exactly the right position to pluck an unlikely catch out of the air above his head. He looks as surprised as anyone!

headshotImage.caption: Wellington Masakadza player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Wellington Masakadza player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Kevin O'Brien c sub (MN Waller) b Masakadza 10 (15b 1x4 0x6 37m) SR: 66.66

dismissalComment.html: caught by Waller in the deep! O'Brien backed himself to beat the fielder with a slog sweep, and he struck the ball really well - but he got rather too far underneath the ball, and achieved more height than distance. Waller set himself under the catch, and waited ... and waited ... and held on! Advantage Zimbabwe now?

dismissalText.commentary: George Dockrell c Nyumbu b Muzarabani 13 (18b 2x4 0x6 36m) SR: 72.22

dismissalComment.html: caught in the gully! Muzarabani charged in and dug the ball in outside off. He got it to leap up at the batsman, and Dockrell tried to ride the bounce, but couldn't. Nyumbu, who'd moved from slip to gully, tumbled forward to hold on to the catch, and Zimbabwe are buzzing now.
